SIMPLE: prudence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prudence
<hw>Pru"dence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>prudentia</ets>, contr. from <ets>providentia</ets>. See
<er>Prudent</er>, and cf. <er>Providence</er>.]</ety> <def>The quality
or state of being prudent; wisdom in the way of caution and provision;
discretion; carefulness; hence, also, economy; frugality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Prudence</qex> is principally in reference to actions to be
done, and due means, order, seasons, and method of doing or not
doing.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Prudence</qex> supposes the value of the end to be assumed,
and refers only to the adaptation of the means. It is the relation of
right means for given ends.</q> <rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Wisdom; forecast; providence; considerateness;
judiciousness; discretion; caution; circumspection; judgment. See
<er>Wisdom</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prudency</ent>⟦br⟧
